{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"Now, have any of y'all ever looked up this word?"},{"time":4000,"text":"You know, in a dictionary? (Laughter) Yeah, that's what I thought."},{"time":8000,"text":"How about this word?"},{"time":10000,"text":"Here, I'll show it to you."},{"time":11000,"text":"Lexicography: the practice of compiling dictionaries."},{"time":14000,"text":"Notice -- we're very specific -- that word \"compile.\""},{"time":17000,"text":"The dictionary is not carved out of a piece of granite,"},{"time":20000,"text":"out of a lump of rock. It's made up of lots of little bits."},{"time":23000,"text":"It's little discrete --"},{"time":24000,"text":"that's spelled D-I-S-C-R-E-T-E -- bits."},{"time":28000,"text":"And those bits are words."}]},{"cues":[{"time":30000,"text":"Now one of the perks of being a lexicographer --"},{"time":34000,"text":"besides getting to come to TED -- is that you get to say really fun words,"},{"time":37000,"text":"like lexicographical."},{"time":40000,"text":"Lexicographical has this great pattern:"},{"time":42000,"text":"it's called a double dactyl. And just by saying double dactyl,"},{"time":44000,"text":"I've sent the geek needle all the way into the red. (Laughter) (Applause)"},{"time":47000,"text":"But \"lexicographical\" is the same pattern as \"higgledy-piggledy.\""},{"time":51000,"text":"Right? It's a fun word to say,"},{"time":53000,"text":"and I get to say it a lot."},{"time":56000,"text":"Now, one of the non-perks of being a lexicographer"},{"time":59000,"text":"is that people don't usually have a kind of warm, fuzzy, snuggly image of the dictionary."},{"time":64000,"text":"Right? Nobody hugs their dictionaries."},{"time":67000,"text":"But what people really often think about the dictionary is, they think more like this."},{"time":74000,"text":"Just to let you know, I do not have a lexicographical whistle."},{"time":77000,"text":"But people think that my job is to let the good words"},{"time":79000,"text":"make that difficult left-hand turn into the dictionary,"},{"time":82000,"text":"and keep the bad words out."}]},{"cues":[{"time":84000,"text":"But the thing is, I don't want to be a traffic cop."},{"time":87000,"text":"For one thing, I just do not do uniforms."},{"time":91000,"text":"And for another, deciding what words are good"},{"time":95000,"text":"and what words are bad is actually not very easy."},{"time":97000,"text":"And it's not very fun. And when parts of your job are not easy or fun,"},{"time":101000,"text":"you kind of look for an excuse not to do them."},{"time":104000,"text":"So if I had to think of some kind of occupation"},{"time":109000,"text":"as a metaphor for my work, I would much rather be a fisherman."},{"time":115000,"text":"I want to throw my big net into the deep, blue ocean of English"},{"time":118000,"text":"and see what marvelous creatures I can drag up from the bottom."},{"time":122000,"text":"But why do people want me to direct traffic, when I would much rather go fishing?"},{"time":127000,"text":"Well, I blame the Queen."},{"time":129000,"text":"Why do I blame the Queen?"},{"time":131000,"text":"Well, first of all, I blame the Queen because it's funny."},{"time":133000,"text":"But secondly, I blame the Queen because"},{"time":136000,"text":"dictionaries have really not changed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":138000,"text":"Our idea of what a dictionary is has not changed since her reign."},{"time":140000,"text":"The only thing that Queen Victoria would not be amused by in modern dictionaries"},{"time":146000,"text":"is our inclusion of the F-word, which has happened"},{"time":149000,"text":"in American dictionaries since 1965."},{"time":151000,"text":"So, there's this guy, right? Victorian era."},{"time":154000,"text":"James Murray, first editor of the Oxford English Dictionary."},{"time":156000,"text":"I do not have that hat. I wish I had that hat."},{"time":159000,"text":"So he's really responsible for a lot of"},{"time":163000,"text":"what we consider modern in dictionaries today."},{"time":165000,"text":"When a guy who looks like that, in that hat,"},{"time":168000,"text":"is the face of modernity, you have a problem."},{"time":175000,"text":"And so, James Murray could get a job on any dictionary today."},{"time":177000,"text":"There'd be virtually no learning curve."}]},{"cues":[{"time":180000,"text":"And of course, a few of us are saying: okay, computers!"},{"time":182000,"text":"Computers! What about computers?"},{"time":184000,"text":"The thing about computers is, I love computers."},{"time":186000,"text":"I mean, I'm a huge geek, I love computers."},{"time":188000,"text":"I would go on a hunger strike before I let them take away Google Book Search from me."},{"time":192000,"text":"But computers don't do much else other than"},{"time":194000,"text":"speed up the process of compiling dictionaries."},{"time":198000,"text":"They don't change the end result."},{"time":202000,"text":"Because what a dictionary is,"},{"time":205000,"text":"is it's Victorian design merged with a little bit of modern propulsion."},{"time":208000,"text":"It's steampunk. What we have is an electric velocipede."},{"time":214000,"text":"You know, we have Victorian design with an engine on it. That's all!"},{"time":217000,"text":"The design has not changed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":220000,"text":"And OK, what about online dictionaries, right?"},{"time":222000,"text":"Online dictionaries must be different."},{"time":225000,"text":"This is the Oxford English Dictionary Online, one of the best online dictionaries."},{"time":227000,"text":"This is my favorite word, by the way."},{"time":228000,"text":"Erinaceous: pertaining to the hedgehog family; of the nature of a hedgehog."},{"time":233000,"text":"Very useful word. So, look at that."},{"time":239000,"text":"Online dictionaries right now are paper thrown up on a screen."},{"time":241000,"text":"This is flat. Look how many links there are in the actual entry: two!"},{"time":246000,"text":"Right? Those little buttons,"},{"time":248000,"text":"I had them all expanded except for the date chart."},{"time":251000,"text":"So there's not very much going on here."},{"time":253000,"text":"There's not a lot of clickiness."},{"time":255000,"text":"And in fact, online dictionaries replicate"},{"time":258000,"text":"almost all the problems of print, except for searchability."},{"time":261000,"text":"And when you improve searchability,"},{"time":263000,"text":"you actually take away the one advantage of print, which is serendipity."},{"time":266000,"text":"Serendipity is when you find things you weren't looking for,"},{"time":269000,"text":"because finding what you are looking for is so damned difficult."}]},{"cues":[{"time":272000,"text":"So -- (Laughter) (Applause) -- now, when you think about this,"},{"time":281000,"text":"what we have here is a ham butt problem."},{"time":284000,"text":"Does everyone know the ham butt problem?"},{"time":286000,"text":"Woman's making a ham for a big, family dinner."},{"time":288000,"text":"She goes to cut the butt off the ham and throw it away,"},{"time":290000,"text":"and she looks at this piece of ham and she's like,"},{"time":291000,"text":"\"This is a perfectly good piece of ham. Why am I throwing this away?\""},{"time":293000,"text":"She thought, \"Well, my mom always did this.\""},{"time":295000,"text":"So she calls up mom, and she says,"},{"time":296000,"text":"\"Mom, why'd you cut the butt off the ham, when you're making a ham?\""},{"time":298000,"text":"She says, \"I don't know, my mom always did it!\""},{"time":301000,"text":"So they call grandma, and grandma says,"},{"time":303000,"text":"\"My pan was too small!\" (Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":307000,"text":"So, it's not that we have good words and bad words."},{"time":311000,"text":"We have a pan that's too small!"},{"time":314000,"text":"You know, that ham butt is delicious! There's no reason to throw it away."},{"time":316000,"text":"The bad words -- see, when people think about a place"},{"time":319000,"text":"and they don't find a place on the map,"},{"time":321000,"text":"they think, \"This map sucks!\""},{"time":323000,"text":"When they find a nightspot or a bar, and it's not in the guidebook,"},{"time":325000,"text":"they're like, \"Ooh, this place must be cool! It's not in the guidebook.\""},{"time":328000,"text":"When they find a word that's not in the dictionary, they think,"},{"time":331000,"text":"\"This must be a bad word.\" Why? It's more likely to be a bad dictionary."},{"time":336000,"text":"Why are you blaming the ham for being too big for the pan?"},{"time":341000,"text":"So, you can't get a smaller ham."},{"time":344000,"text":"The English language is as big as it is."}]},{"cues":[{"time":347000,"text":"So, if you have a ham butt problem,"},{"time":349000,"text":"and you're thinking about the ham butt problem,"},{"time":351000,"text":"the conclusion that it leads you to is inexorable and counterintuitive:"},{"time":356000,"text":"paper is the enemy of words."},{"time":359000,"text":"How can this be? I mean, I love books. I really love books."},{"time":363000,"text":"Some of my best friends are books."},{"time":365000,"text":"But the book is not the best shape for the dictionary."},{"time":370000,"text":"Now they're going to think \"Oh, boy."},{"time":372000,"text":"People are going to take away my beautiful, paper dictionaries?\""},{"time":375000,"text":"No. There will still be paper dictionaries."},{"time":377000,"text":"When we had cars -- when cars became the dominant mode of transportation,"},{"time":381000,"text":"we didn't round up all the horses and shoot them."},{"time":384000,"text":"You know, there're still going to be paper dictionaries,"},{"time":386000,"text":"but it's not going to be the dominant dictionary."},{"time":389000,"text":"The book-shaped dictionary is not going to be the only shape"},{"time":392000,"text":"dictionaries come in. And it's not going to be"},{"time":394000,"text":"the prototype for the shapes dictionaries come in."}]},{"cues":[{"time":398000,"text":"So, think about it this way: if you've got an artificial constraint,"},{"time":402000,"text":"artificial constraints lead to"},{"time":406000,"text":"arbitrary distinctions and a skewed worldview."},{"time":410000,"text":"What if biologists could only study animals"},{"time":413000,"text":"that made people go, \"Aww.\" Right?"},{"time":415000,"text":"What if we made aesthetic judgments about animals,"},{"time":417000,"text":"and only the ones we thought were cute were the ones that we could study?"},{"time":422000,"text":"We'd know a whole lot about charismatic megafauna,"},{"time":426000,"text":"and not very much about much else."},{"time":428000,"text":"And I think this is a problem."},{"time":430000,"text":"I think we should study all the words,"},{"time":432000,"text":"because when you think about words, you can make beautiful expressions"},{"time":437000,"text":"from very humble parts."},{"time":441000,"text":"Lexicography is really more about material science."},{"time":445000,"text":"We are studying the tolerances of the materials"},{"time":448000,"text":"that you use to build the structure of your expression:"},{"time":451000,"text":"your speeches and your writing. And then, often people say to me,"},{"time":458000,"text":"\"Well, OK, how do I know that this word is real?\""},{"time":463000,"text":"They think, \"OK, if we think words are the tools"},{"time":470000,"text":"that we use to build the expressions of our thoughts,"},{"time":472000,"text":"how can you say that screwdrivers are better than hammers?"},{"time":475000,"text":"How can you say that a sledgehammer is better than a ball-peen hammer?\""},{"time":478000,"text":"They're just the right tools for the job."}]},{"cues":[{"time":481000,"text":"And so people say to me, \"How do I know if a word is real?\""},{"time":484000,"text":"You know, anybody who's read a children's book"},{"time":487000,"text":"knows that love makes things real."},{"time":491000,"text":"If you love a word, use it. That makes it real."},{"time":496000,"text":"Being in the dictionary is an artificial distinction."},{"time":499000,"text":"It doesn't make a word any more real than any other way."},{"time":502000,"text":"If you love a word, it becomes real."},{"time":506000,"text":"So if we're not worrying about directing traffic,"},{"time":509000,"text":"if we've transcended paper, if we are worrying less"},{"time":514000,"text":"about control and more about description,"},{"time":518000,"text":"then we can think of the English language"},{"time":520000,"text":"as being this beautiful mobile."},{"time":523000,"text":"And any time one of those little parts of the mobile changes,"},{"time":525000,"text":"is touched, any time you touch a word,"},{"time":528000,"text":"you use it in a new context, you give it a new connotation,"},{"time":530000,"text":"you verb it, you make the mobile move."},{"time":533000,"text":"You didn't break it. It's just in a new position,"},{"time":537000,"text":"and that new position can be just as beautiful."}]},{"cues":[{"time":540000,"text":"Now, if you're no longer a traffic cop --"},{"time":544000,"text":"the problem with being a traffic cop is"},{"time":546000,"text":"there can only be so many traffic cops in any one intersection,"},{"time":549000,"text":"or the cars get confused. Right?"},{"time":552000,"text":"But if your goal is no longer to direct the traffic,"},{"time":555000,"text":"but maybe to count the cars that go by, then more eyeballs are better."},{"time":559000,"text":"You can ask for help!"},{"time":561000,"text":"If you ask for help, you get more done. And we really need help."},{"time":565000,"text":"Library of Congress: 17 million books,"},{"time":568000,"text":"of which half are in English."},{"time":571000,"text":"If only one out of every 10 of those books"},{"time":575000,"text":"had a word that's not in the dictionary in it,"},{"time":577000,"text":"that would be equivalent to more than two unabridged dictionaries."}]},{"cues":[{"time":580000,"text":"And I find an un-dictionaried word --"},{"time":583000,"text":"a word like \"un-dictionaried,\" for example --"},{"time":585000,"text":"in almost every book I read. What about newspapers?"},{"time":590000,"text":"Newspaper archive goes back to 1759,"},{"time":595000,"text":"58.1 million newspaper pages. If only one in 100"},{"time":600000,"text":"of those pages had an un-dictionaried word on it,"},{"time":603000,"text":"it would be an entire other OED."},{"time":606000,"text":"That's 500,000 more words. So that's a lot."},{"time":611000,"text":"And I'm not even talking about magazines. I'm not talking about blogs --"},{"time":614000,"text":"and I find more new words on BoingBoing in a given week"},{"time":616000,"text":"than I do Newsweek or Time."},{"time":618000,"text":"There's a lot going on there."}]},{"cues":[{"time":620000,"text":"And I'm not even talking about polysemy,"},{"time":622000,"text":"which is the greedy habit some words have of taking"},{"time":625000,"text":"more than one meaning for themselves."},{"time":630000,"text":"So if you think of the word \"set,\" a set can be a badger's burrow,"},{"time":634000,"text":"a set can be one of the pleats in an Elizabethan ruff,"},{"time":637000,"text":"and there's one numbered definition in the OED."},{"time":639000,"text":"The OED has 33 different numbered definitions for set."},{"time":642000,"text":"Tiny, little word, 33 numbered definitions."},{"time":645000,"text":"One of them is just labeled \"miscellaneous technical senses.\""},{"time":650000,"text":"Do you know what that says to me?"},{"time":651000,"text":"That says to me, it was Friday afternoon and somebody wanted to go down the pub. (Laughter)"},{"time":656000,"text":"That's a lexicographical cop out,"},{"time":658000,"text":"to say, \"miscellaneous technical senses.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":660000,"text":"So, we have all these words, and we really need help!"},{"time":664000,"text":"And the thing is, we could ask for help --"},{"time":667000,"text":"asking for help's not that hard."},{"time":668000,"text":"I mean, lexicography is not rocket science."},{"time":671000,"text":"See, I just gave you a lot of words and a lot of numbers,"},{"time":674000,"text":"and this is more of a visual explanation."},{"time":676000,"text":"If we think of the dictionary as being the map of the English language,"},{"time":679000,"text":"these bright spots are what we know about,"},{"time":681000,"text":"and the dark spots are where we are in the dark."},{"time":684000,"text":"If that was the map of all the words in American English, we don't know very much."},{"time":689000,"text":"And we don't even know the shape of the language."},{"time":692000,"text":"If this was the dictionary -- if this was the map of American English --"},{"time":695000,"text":"look, we have a kind of lumpy idea of Florida,"},{"time":698000,"text":"but there's no California!"},{"time":701000,"text":"We're missing California from American English."},{"time":704000,"text":"We just don't know enough, and we don't even know that we're missing California."},{"time":709000,"text":"We don't even see that there's a gap on the map."}]},{"cues":[{"time":711000,"text":"So again, lexicography is not rocket science."},{"time":714000,"text":"But even if it were, rocket science is being done"},{"time":717000,"text":"by dedicated amateurs these days. You know?"},{"time":721000,"text":"It can't be that hard to find some words!"},{"time":725000,"text":"So, enough scientists in other disciplines"},{"time":728000,"text":"are really asking people to help, and they're doing a good job of it."},{"time":731000,"text":"For instance, there's eBird, where amateur birdwatchers"},{"time":733000,"text":"can upload information about their bird sightings."},{"time":735000,"text":"And then, ornithologists can go"},{"time":737000,"text":"and help track populations, migrations, etc."}]},{"cues":[{"time":740000,"text":"And there's this guy, Mike Oates. Mike Oates lives in the U.K."},{"time":743000,"text":"He's a director of an electroplating company."},{"time":747000,"text":"He's found more than 140 comets."},{"time":750000,"text":"He's found so many comets, they named a comet after him."},{"time":753000,"text":"It's kind of out past Mars. It's a hike."},{"time":754000,"text":"I don't think he's getting his picture taken there anytime soon."},{"time":756000,"text":"But he found 140 comets without a telescope."},{"time":760000,"text":"He downloaded data from the NASA SOHO satellite,"},{"time":763000,"text":"and that's how he found them."},{"time":765000,"text":"If we can find comets without a telescope,"},{"time":769000,"text":"shouldn't we be able to find words?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":771000,"text":"Now, y'all know where I'm going with this."},{"time":773000,"text":"Because I'm going to the Internet, which is where everybody goes."},{"time":776000,"text":"And the Internet is great for collecting words,"},{"time":778000,"text":"because the Internet's full of collectors."},{"time":779000,"text":"And this is a little-known technological fact about the Internet,"},{"time":782000,"text":"but the Internet is actually made up of words and enthusiasm."},{"time":785000,"text":"And words and enthusiasm actually happen to be"},{"time":790000,"text":"the recipe for lexicography. Isn't that great?"},{"time":793000,"text":"So there are a lot of really good word-collecting sites out there right now,"},{"time":797000,"text":"but the problem with some of them is that they're not scientific enough."},{"time":799000,"text":"They show the word, but they don't show any context."},{"time":802000,"text":"Where did it come from? Who said it?"},{"time":804000,"text":"What newspaper was it in? What book?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":806000,"text":"Because a word is like an archaeological artifact."},{"time":810000,"text":"If you don't know the provenance or the source of the artifact,"},{"time":813000,"text":"it's not science, it's a pretty thing to look at."},{"time":816000,"text":"So a word without its source is like a cut flower."},{"time":819000,"text":"You know, it's pretty to look at for a while, but then it dies."},{"time":823000,"text":"It dies too fast."},{"time":824000,"text":"So, this whole time I've been saying,"},{"time":828000,"text":"\"The dictionary, the dictionary, the dictionary, the dictionary.\""},{"time":830000,"text":"Not \"a dictionary,\" or \"dictionaries.\" And that's because,"},{"time":833000,"text":"well, people use the dictionary to stand for the whole language."},{"time":836000,"text":"They use it synecdochically."},{"time":839000,"text":"And one of the problems of knowing a word like \"synecdochically\""},{"time":842000,"text":"is that you really want an excuse to say \"synecdochically.\""},{"time":845000,"text":"This whole talk has just been an excuse to get me to the point"},{"time":847000,"text":"where I could say \"synecdochically\" to all of you."},{"time":849000,"text":"So I'm really sorry. But when you use a part of something --"},{"time":852000,"text":"like the dictionary is a part of the language,"},{"time":854000,"text":"or a flag stands for the United States, it's a symbol of the country --"},{"time":859000,"text":"then you're using it synecdochically."},{"time":863000,"text":"But the thing is, we could make the dictionary the whole language."},{"time":867000,"text":"If we get a bigger pan, then we can put all the words in."},{"time":871000,"text":"We can put in all the meanings."},{"time":875000,"text":"Doesn't everyone want more meaning in their lives?"},{"time":879000,"text":"And we can make the dictionary not just be a symbol of the language --"},{"time":883000,"text":"we can make it be the whole language."}]},{"cues":[{"time":886000,"text":"You see, what I'm really hoping for is that my son,"},{"time":888000,"text":"who turns seven this month -- I want him to barely remember"},{"time":891000,"text":"that this is the form factor that dictionaries used to come in."},{"time":896000,"text":"This is what dictionaries used to look like."},{"time":898000,"text":"I want him to think of this kind of dictionary as an eight-track tape."},{"time":900000,"text":"It's a format that died because it wasn't useful enough."},{"time":904000,"text":"It wasn't really what people needed."},{"time":907000,"text":"And the thing is, if we can put in all the words,"},{"time":910000,"text":"no longer have that artificial distinction between good and bad,"},{"time":914000,"text":"we can really describe the language like scientists."},{"time":917000,"text":"We can leave the aesthetic judgments to the writers and the speakers."},{"time":919000,"text":"If we can do that, then I can spend all my time fishing,"},{"time":923000,"text":"and I don't have to be a traffic cop anymore."},{"time":928000,"text":"Thank you very much for your kind attention."}]}]}